            <h2>Negations Overview</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">N</span>egations in Old English are different from negations
                in modern English in three ways.
            </p>
            <h3>Word Order</h3>
            <p>The negative particle always precedes the verb and often starts a sentence or construction. For example,
                '<em>Ne com heo - She didn't come</em>' (literally
                '<em>not come she</em>')' or '<em>Ne stel ðu - Do not steal</em>' (literally '<em>no steal you</em>').
                It should be noted that auixlliary verbs like 'do' or 'can' are not routinely used in negative
                constructions the way they are in modern English. For example, 'I do not like', 'I cannot come'.
                Examine the sentence,
                '<em>Ne mette he nan gebun land - He did not find unoccupied land</em>'.
            </p>
