            <h3>Double Negatives</h3>
            <p>In modern English, negatives cancel each other out - so 'I do not not love Old English' means that you, in
                fact, do love it. In Old English, double negation simply emphasises the negation, and it is common to find negation
                applied to every word that can be made negative in a single sentence. If you are unfamiliar with how negation works,
                this can make the sentence very hard to read. For example, '<em>ða ða we hit now&aelig;ðer ne selfe ne lufodon ne eac oðrum mannum ne lefdon - When we neither loved it ourselves, nor even allowed it to
                    others</em>'.
            </p>
